,Recommended,237740,8317119,"Posted: 26 December, 2013",all,Ben Rowland,"Having been an AVGN fan for a number of years, I was excited to see what the first official video game based on the character would be like. For the three people around who aren't familiar with AVGN, he's a character whose life mission is to play some of the worst video games from the retro era. The original focus was the Nintendo Entertainment System, but games for others systems have also been covered. The brainchild of filmmaker James Rolfe, the nerd is a loud, vulgar, beer-swilling cad who bemoans his need to play these horrible games. The pain is eased in no small measure by his love for Rolling Rock beer.Angry Video Game Nerd Adventure is very much a fan service game, so it's the dedicated videos of his web-based show that will get the most out of the experience. Borrowing heavily from the 8-bit Mega Man games, the gameplay is classic, tough-as-nails platforming with insane traps, waves of enemeis and frequent deaths. Fans of the aforementioned Mega Man, Metroid, Castlevania and Contra games will appreciate the old school difficulty. While one-hit kills are frequent, you do have a life meter (a line of beer bottles) and you can find health power-ups throughout the level. Searching the levels also unlocks new playable characters. Each level is based on a trope from the AVGN series, with various in-jokes to the series providing much enjoyment to hardcore fans.While your enjoyment of the crass humor depends on how familiar with the AVGN series you are, the gameplay is accessible for most retro game fans. Your goal is to get from one end of the level to the next and defeat a boss, very simple premise, but the difficulty makes it an endurance test of trial and error. This is by design, since the game is a homage to an era where video games didn't hold your hand and ""Game Over"" meant just that. There is an easier difficulty setting for those who want an easier ride, but the true risk and reward comes with the more challenging settings. Since the platforming needs to be precise, I highly recommend playing with a controller over the mouse and keyboard. The game plays beautifully with my Xbox 360 controller, with fast, responsive and tight controls making the game a blast...even if I'm constantly dying,AVGN Adventures is not a perfect game, but it's a joy to play if you're a fan of retro side-scrollers and especially fans of the AVGN show. The full price is a little steep for some, but those who make the investment are in for a great time."
