76561198044917795,Recommended,237740,7979299,"Posted: 8 December, 2013",all,Pale Caesar,"I recommend this game, but with stipulations.(1) You have to appreciate 2D sidescrollers. Unlike Super Meat Boy, which at its most basic is attainable to almost anybody (thanks in no small part to it's quick respawn and limited screen length), AVGNA is rooted much more in old school games (as is to be expected). If you can't stand 2D sidescrollers from the NES or SNES era, you WON'T enjoy this game.(2) You have to expect its difficulty. Beings as it was devised to emulate the atrocities (to an extent) that The Nerd reviews on his videos, this game emulates the difficulty perfectly. I didn't even attempt beating the game on normal or hard, where you have limited lives. It took me over 100 lives to beat the game on easy. Am I that bad? Probably; my hardcore gaming days are over. But the game is also just that difficult. You CAN'T get frustrated with the game, or else you will wind up making mistakes that will set you back (or just make you more angry).Those stipulations aside, the game is enjoyable, and the final battle/stage will surely be a great ""surprise"" for any fan of AVGN. In fact, fans of AVGN will love the amount of references to the popular character and his videos. But I will say this - the game is short. The majority of its length of play comes from dying (and there are plenty of one-hit-kill objects in the game) and resuming at the previous checkpoint.If you really like AVGN and can handle the above stipulations, the game is worth the price (though a sale price would help me encourage that). If you've never heard of AVGN and happened to stumble onto this game based on its old-school look, be advised of the above and note that there is LOTS of swearing in the game, and many humorous references will be missed."
