,Not Recommended,237740,19027775,"Posted: 11 November, 2015",all,Anema86,"In their zeal to make a game that features all the things the AVGN has complained about, they managed to make a game that is only slightly below average. One would expect that the novelty would make up for it--having useless power-ups, cheap deaths, and all that were intentional design choices, after all, so you know that you're buying into that when you buy the game. In addition to this, though, AVGN Adventures has clear problems that should have been fixed.Serious Problems:Movement. The characters move with all the precision of Meat Boy. This makes playing the level ""Beat Em and Eat Em"", which features a ton of slippery surfaces, even more frustating. The imprecise controls are one thing, but there is something else that combines with them that, honestly, threaten to make AVGN Adventures unplayable. And that ""something"" is:The camera. Rather than centering the AVGN, AVGN Adventures has him just slightly to the left of the center when you're moving to the right, and just slightly to the right of the camera when you're moving left. Changing directions on the fly becomes borderline impossible, because the camera shifts, too, which can and will totally screw up whatever difficult platforming section you were trying to get through. And that's a problem because of:Knockback. The knockback in this game is weird. I'd tentatively say that the knockback consists primarily of you getting hit UP, not backward or forward. In good games, knockback is predictable, and can even be taken advantage of. There's none of that here, and the unusual knockback will be a source of many deaths, simply because it's non-standard and very difficult to get used to. And, naturally, there aren't very many platforming sections that don't feature enemies coming at you, because:The level design in AVGN Adventures is horrendous. It's dull, uninspired, and boring. As ProJared rightly pointed out, there are actually only a few enemy types in the game, and what they look like simply varies based on what stage you're in.And, as ProJared also points out, the developers substituted instant death blocks instead of creative level design. Predictable disappearing/reappearing Deathblocks appear in almost every stage, and they're not really difficult to get past; it just requires you to wait. There's a lot of waiting in this game. Something ♥♥♥♥balls is the most obvious offender: half of the stage is filled with instant death beams that are ridiculously easy to avoid and accomplish little more than making you wait for 3 seconds every 15 steps. This will almost certainly be the first level that you beat without dying at all.And you'll be glad to not die often, because dying is tedious. Even though there's an obscene number of checkpoints, even on Normal mode, death is a pain in the♥♥♥♥♥because the developers thought it would be funny to have a random AVGN statement about what he'd rather do than continue playing--every. single. time. you. die.And you die a lot. That's kinda the point of the game, supposedly being Nintendo Hard. But it's not. This is AVGN Adventure's main flaw: it PRETENDS to be Nintendo Hard by throwing a lot of cheap deaths at the player, but it's actually a very easy game. This is no I Wanna Be the Guy, which throws up a lot of cheap deaths AND is Nintendo Hard. I can't quantify what the difference is.It's a short game. It can be beaten in just a few hours, which makes that $9.99 price tag WAY too high. For $2.99 or $3.99, I could recommend this. But at $9.99? You're paying more than $1 per hour for an experience that... just isn't that good.People often say that the music in AVGN Adventures is awesome. But that's not true. The only level in the game that has good music is Something ♥♥♥♥balls, and I'll give it that--that level's music is incredibly awesome. But that's only one-ninth of the game; what about the other 8 levels? They're nothing special, and a few are actually annoying. One stage has really awesome music, but 8/9 of the stages have boring, uninteresting music, yet the game is still cited as having awesome music. It doesn't. It has one stage that has awesome music. The rest of the music kinda sucks.Almost all of the bosses are the same, too, including the final boss. There are one or two exceptions, but most of the bosses just move around in a figure 8 while shooting things.So here you have a game that would have quickly faded into obscurity if it didn't have the AVGN's name attached to it. There's a sequel coming out relatively soon, and my sincerest hope is that the developers took a few lessons in creative level design before then, because I don't consider filling a stage with death blocks, using only 5 or 6 enemies, and making players wait constantly to be ""creative"". Even the final boss is just a rehash of several other bosses in the game, with nothing unique or new going on anywhere at all. Take that $9.99 and buy the Mega Man Legacy Collection instead. You'll get way more entertainment out of Mega Man than AVGN Adventures.To that, you're probably saying, ""Well, duh!""And that's my point EXACTLY. They're both $9.99."
