,Recommended,237740,19740472,"Posted: 16 December, 2015",all,MeleeKirby,"AVGN Adventures, as you probably figured looking at the screenshots, is a sidescrolling retro style platformer. What makes this one different from all the other retro style platformers is that it is based entirely around the concept and exploits of the Angry Video Game Nerd.AVGN decides to play a pretty bad game, as he usually does. However, this game decides to pull him through the TV, sucking him into the world of terrible videogames and bad videogame tropes. The plot is very simple, and only really serves the purpose of giving you the setup to actually play through the adventure.If you're not really a fan of the AVGN series of videos, then this isn't for you; the whole game is designed to be a playable homage to the Nerd and everything that the fans love about him and what he does. The whole game is jam-packed full of references that most people familiar with the series will get and appreciate, as well as a number of deliberately bad game design choices that make their way in as a result of his frequent complaining of said issues in many of his reviews. It all adds up to a game with themes that are very faithful to the titular hero.The levels are deliberately very tricky, and oftentimes you'll find you die a lot in each one. Most of the levels often have instances of trial and error. You will most likely die not knowing how to navigate certain obstacles the very first time, or not react quickly enough not knowing what's about to come. To offset this style of difficulty, the player is given a total of 30 lives to work with. This is usually enough to make it from beginning to end of a level. But it's in this feature that lies my main criticism with the game.The system of 30 lives to make it through any given level is fine, however my main issue with this is that upon completing a level, your remaining number of lives will carry over to the level you play next. This means that unavoidably you will always start subsequent levels with significantly fewer lives to work with, and you might find that you won't even have anywhere close enough to beat a level the first time. Get a Game Over, and you lose your checkpoint progress.There is no way to reset your lives count except by getting a Game Over, either. I've tried to save, quit and come back into the existing save to see if that would work. Sadly the save does save your current lives count, meaning it was intentionally designed that way. So if you begin with a meager 5 lives, you will either want to just kill them off at the start or use them for practice in the early part of the level, because you're probably not going to get too far with them.That issue aside, AVGN Adventures is a really fun game for fans with great graphics and awesome 8-bit music. Highly recommened if you love AVGN!"
,Recommended,237740,12648680,"Posted: 26 October, 2014",all,NyoshKosh B'Gosh,"The humor is exactly what I expected from the AVGN.  I don't always find it funny, and I generally enjoy Jame's videos more for the information and content than his ""angry"" rants.  However, this game has it's funny moments - and the cameos always made me laugh.  But most importantly is that THIS GAME IS INCREDIBLE.   If you play on the easiest setting, and are an experienced platform gamer, you should be able to play through it withing a couple hours of game time (if that).  But then this feels like a classic ""go back, play it again, do it better, find everything, beat it on higher difficulty"" style of game play.The controls are incredible - and I use a Logitech F310, so nothing perfect, but the game feels amazing.  The contoller support is wonderful, as well.It plays in a similar manner to a Mega Man game with it's intense platforming... but it runs much faster and much more smoothly.  I would honestly love to find more games that play just like this.  I can't get enough of it!"
