,Recommended,237740,11917497,"Posted: 29 August, 2014",all,Olde,"Wow, I'm very surprised to see some hate for this game. Let me try to be as objective as possible here. AVGNA is a game that, let's face it, is designed around the problems that James Rolfe has pointed out in his over 100 videos for his popular web series, the Angry Video Game Nerd. AVGNA is mainly a tribute to his legacy of video reviews, but which manages to capture the spirit of that show while also providing humorous dialogue and some pretty fun levels. The control is very good (best played with a controller), the graphics are appealing, the health pickups and one-ups are relatively plentiful, and there are numerous checkpoints scattered generously across the levels. The music is very catchy and gives the game a strong sense of energy. I also enjoyed how you can play as different characters who have different weapons and abilities, if you could find them.Now let's get to the major complaints. Yes, this game is full of cheap kills. That's part of the point. This game is full of meta jokes because you're playing as the Nerd who has to fight the summation of obstacles that have plagued so many of the terrible games from his youth. As I was playing, I was really thinking ""Wow, this stuff really must've been horrendous"" in reference to the games he had to beat for his show. But the beautiful thing about this game is that I feel it never exceeds the threshold. The ""cheap"" sections really aren't that long, and the difficult areas are always preceded by easier sections that are meant to teach you the tricks or gimmicks of each level.For people who are debating whether or not to buy this game, I would say that if you're a fan of AVGN and you like platformers or played them as a kid, give this one a go. In terms of 2-D platformers that have come out recently, this is definitely one of the best. The level design actually had quite a bit of thought put in, and even though it can be frustrating, if you're smart enough to figure out basic patterns and patient enough to repeat certain sections, you won't regret getting this game. I've been a big fan of James for years and I think that this game stays true to the basic feel of the videos and the attitude he exudes as the Nerd. Plus I loved the humor and self-referential jokes.To respond to negative reviews, here's what I have to say: There's no way I can understand complaints about this game being too difficult. Compared to some of the games people of James's generation played growing up, like Super Ghouls and Ghosts, Silver Surfer, and Battletoads, AVGNA is a walk in the park. AVGNA was made as both a parody of bad games and as a send-up of the games that defined ""Nintendo-hard."" Kids these days are coddled. This game isn't really that tough when you get down to it, nor is it unfair. As for complaints that the game is padded, you could say that for any platformer. The only platformer I've ever seen with a decent storyline was Braid, and this game is definitely not that. Is AVGNA worth $10? I suppose it's subjective, but I had more fun with this game than I did with several other more expensive games that may have technically better graphics and more of a story but fail at having an interesting character or unique feel. This game doesn't feel recycled, it feels new and different, in spite of its origins from past games. In other words, it synthesizes elements from both the AVGN show and from the games themselves, but I felt that when notoriously bad elements were included, it was always for the sake of humor, and they were treated in a relatively fair manner, even though some people find the game to be grinding."
