,Recommended,237740,9444441,"Posted: 12 March, 2014",all,Jr Jam,angry potatoes on a soup
,Recommended,237740,9535887,"Posted: 17 March, 2014",all,Colonoctopus,"First of all, let me start off by saying that this is a fun game. It's pretty much all I've been playing recently; the controls are nice, the levels have variety, and you get a great feeling of accomplishment when you get past hard parts of the game or beat a boss. However, there are a few things that have really annoyed me, and one of them was enough to make me stop playing the game entirely.My biggest complaint is that there are no save points. There are checkpoints that you respawn at, and the game saves every time you beat a world, but if you quit in the middle of a level, you won't be able to go back to where you were. This really ♥♥♥♥ed me off, because I was fighting the final boss at the end of the hardest stage in the game (which took me 20 minutes to beat) when I had to leave. When I came back, I couldn't resume the fight. Frankly, there's not much of a chance of me going back to playing it anytime soon, simply because of this.As for my smaller complaints, some of them may be by design, but that doesn't stop them from being annoying as hell. Whenever you get hit by an enemy, you lose all momentum. Normally this wouldn't be too bad, but the amount of enemies and hazards the game designers put before or in the middle of big jumps is just ridiculous at times.The standard short invincibility period when you are damaged seems to be present in this game, but it doesn't protect you from most enviromental hazards. This one is really a tiny annoyance, and it becomes less bothersome as you get used to it, but I still feel that potential buyers should know.As well as losing momentum when the enemies hit you, you sometimes move slightly in a random direction. There's one part of the game where this is especially annoying, where even the slightest hit from an enemy will send you a pixel to the left straight into a skull block.Another larger complaint is that you take too long to respawn. In other extremely hard, death-comes-in-an-instant games (Hotline Miami, Super Meat Boy), you respawn instantly when you die. In AVGN Adventures, you have to wait at the game over screen so that the game can show you its novel at first, but eventually just annoying randomly generated nerd quotes. This can be very annoying in the parts of the game that are filled with the skull blocks that instakill you when you touch them.Another warning to potential buyers: This game is mostly fanservice. If you're not into the Angry Video Game Nerd, then this won't be very fun for you. Unfortunately, even the fan service aspect of the game leaves something to be desired. It's filled with funny references, but other than that, not much of the dialogue and level design really reflects the show all that much.Overall, it's a fun but extremely flawed game, and definitely worth it if you're an AVGN fan looking for a couple hours of (extremely frustrating) fun."
