76561198118975055,Recommended,237740,8749163,"Posted: 17 January, 2014",all,Joji of the Midnight,AVGN Adventures is so Hard it's GOOD. i feel Rewarded Everytime for Beating a Level Boss With Only Two or one Life Everytime and it Feels Awesome.
,Recommended,237740,8837508,"Posted: 24 January, 2014",all,CantyCanadian,"This is one of the game I have the most mixed feeling about. Being one of the game I was most hyped for, having the main character being one of my favorite video-maker on the internet and one of the pioneer of modern video-format video game reviews, but does the qualities of the game finishes there?First of, the gameplay. The nerd, being a player of old school games, had to have something resembling this in his own game. So, the gameplay is a mix of multiple games, but mainly from 2D shooters like Megaman. You're able to shoot (with the nerd) in eight directions and can jump. That's about it.During the game, you can find other characters that can help you during your adventure, three of them being even playable. The first one is The Guitar Guy, who is the creator of AVGN's theme song. His weapon of choice is his trusty guitar that shoots waves of sounds that passes through wall, making some parts in some level easier to complete.Next, we have Mike, James Rolfe's friend and the 'co-founder' of AVGN. His weapon is a lightsaber that only attacks at melee range, but is the fastest weapon. He also jumps higher than any character and has the power to see special blocks that can be destroyed with his saber to reveal items, like in Castlevania.Finally, we have... Bullsh*t Man. For this review, I'll just call him BSM. BSM is a strange case, being a character from another sere run byCinemasacre.com, James' website. His power is the 'sh*tdouken' where he throws a poop projectile that suffers from gravity, making some kind of arc. His main ability, however, is a fart jump, allowing to jump in mid-air to make platform parts easier.For the gameplay, we also have collectibles. You can collect beer bottles for health, Nerd heads for lives and a Super Scope for a temporary power boost. You can also find the Nerd's friend that will give you tons of power ups while saying funny stuff. They are well hidden and make it worth to get off the main track to explore a bit.To finish with the collectibles, we have the special powerups. There is the 'rock' which is... a rock. This is a reference to Friday the 13th on the NES. It's literally the worst weapon in the game. Next, we have the glitch goblin that freezes any enemies or obstacles to pass them easily. And we have Super Mecha Death Christ, which is a fully loaded Jesus that kills everything on the screen.Sadly, even with the amount of collectibles you can get, the gameplay stops there. Sure, you have some sections where you ride either Santa Claus or a fire shark, but the game doesn't really change much. Not that it's a bad thing, but it might get stale for some players.This game, however, has a different meaning for the word fun. ""The best part of a journey is the travel, not the destination"", this game make it so you wish there was no travel. You are a god (or too young to play) if you don't swear at least once during the game. This piece of software sh*t is made to make you suffer.The difficulty, however, was expected. There is different difficulty option that changes the lives and beer bottle count, but even at easy, it can be hell to some players. I could say that it's a fun game, but it's f*cking hard. Seriously, there is a reason why there aren't that much people who did it in the maximum difficulty (being hardcore 0 lives, one hit point). Want a challenge or miss the NES era, grab this game.Which this game is challenging and fun, the replayability is kind of non-existant. Sure, you unlock some new difficulties, but the experience doesn't change. Worst, you know where the easter eggs, easy to grab powerups and death traps are, making the journey less fun. Plus, being only a game that last around 3 hours before finishing doesn't help.Then, the art department, namely the graphics and sound. From the mouth of the developpers : ""We tried to stick to some kind of 10-bit display. 8-bit didn't have enough details while 16-bit wasn't enough old school."" This statement make it so that this game has a style of its own and it really shows how much you can do with it. The appearance of the game is really good and each level has a different theme, making the backgrounds vibrant and ever-changing.The soundtrack is simply awesome. For a game about a swearing nerd, the music really sets the mood for some balls to the walls action. Some of those tracks could make it to my music player if I wouldn't be so lazy. The sound effects, for the most part, are pretty good. Each sounds are different enough so that it doesn't sound like recycled bleeps and bloops and it sounds like it could belong on an old console.This game is obviously a gift to the fans of the nerd. It's a challenging game, but that's about it. Both for fans and non-fans, you shouldn't buy it at full price (15$) and wait for a promotion, which happens very often. Even then, I think that only fans could really enjoy this experience due to the sheer amount of easter eggs related to the f*cking nerd there is hidden in this.Gameplay : 6/10Fun : 5/10Graphics : 7/10Music : 9/10Result : 6.75/10   Good-ish Game."
