,Recommended,237740,26721524,"Posted: 20 November, 2016",all,paralistalon,"Even if you're not familiar with the AVGN, this game still impresses as a throwback to the 8-bit Megaman games.  Yes, it's a lot harder, but they give you 30 lives and constant continue points on the normal difficulty, so it's not much of an issue.  It's very doable even with a keyboard.  Once you've memorized how to get past the hardest parts, and as long as you're taking your time, it's not even that bad.  Of course, the game basically taunts you into rushing head first into the various obstacles, and by the tenth time you've died to one, you end up playing so recklessly and ""on tilt"" that you just keep dieing, with the Nerd character giving a hilarious randomly generated complaint after each death.  The game is a bit short, like a traditional Megaman game (8 stages and an amazingly evil final stage) but for $10, it's totally worth the money.  There are a few secrets to find, like unlocking some bonus characters, and there's always the added replay value of trying to complete the game on the hard difficulty, which limits the number of lives and continues you get."
76561198166911326,Not Recommended,237740,26723668,"Posted: 20 November, 2016",all,Thing 1,poop
76561198254847438,Recommended,237740,18493276,"Posted: 15 October, 2015",all,Mighty Schnitzel,"I really enjoy my time with this game!While I am not a fan of games that try too hard to 'bring back the past' by featuring 8-bit graphics and old-school mechanics borrowed from NES games, I do enjoy hard 2D platforming games that require patience and memorization.AVGN Adventures is definitely it's own thing and does not rely on you having any sort of nostalgia for the genre. It has a distinct visual style, very well implemented mechanics that are both old-school and new, and is just generally one of the few examples of a modern 2D platformer done right. Sure, there is a little bit of trial and error, but I would say that patient players will not find themselves frustrated with the level design and the death traps. The level design is devilish, but not unfair! Really, all of your skill depends on whether or not you can remain calm and on how fast you pick up on shortcuts through levels and boss fights. Secrets are hard to find (I would say impossible) and I would suggest looking at a guide to find all the cameos and characters to help you on your way through any of the higher difficulties.If you are a AVGN fan, you'll definitely get more of a kick out of the game as there's lots of references. I can imagine the 'dialogue' in the game being grating to non-fans as you can't turn it off. That quickly becomes a problem for anyone that wants to replay the game multiple times, as the dialogue still remains there.The game can be beaten in an hour on lower difficulties, but the game banks on you replaying it on higher unlockable difficulties. If you like earning achievements, this game makes it really satisfying to get them (for the most part). I played it for 8 hours according to my timer, and I have only beaten the game on 2 difficulties so far (Normal and Old-School). All that changes is that you have more limited amounts of lives and harder to beat enemies to face (as well as other small things).All in all, AVGN Adventures is definitely a memorable 2D Platformer and definitely an instant-classic for AVGN fans. For everyone else, though, this will just be a fun experience for a few hours. I recommend it to anyone who likes a simple game with challenging level design and a lust for earning achievements."
