76561198080018990,Recommended,237740,18346225,"Posted: 5 October, 2015",all,Team Hamster,Angry Video Game Nerd Adventures is like a trip down memory lane for AVGN fans. If you really like The AVGN then this game is for you. It has alot of the same humor that is found in the videos and many charactors and settings are in the game that are direct references to certain episodes of AVGN. If your not familier or a fan of AVGN you may like this game less however if your a fan of older video games such as side scrolling action shooter platformers I would give this game a try. It is however insanely difficult and that is the way it is meant to be. Also what I found really interesting and fun was the ability to play not just as AVGN but Mike which is pretty cool among others. This game was a bit short however but I guess the real challenge is seeing how much better you can do going thru it again and dieing a little less.
,Recommended,237740,17776973,"Posted: 29 August, 2015",all,Clarky,"I intially went into this game with low expectations I have been dissapointed with licensed product before (having played a myriad of movie tie-in shovelware titles in my youth.) However I was very impressed with AVGN Adventures, a game that will appeal to both long-time fans of The Nerd and fans of hardcore retro platformers.This title was released in 2013, developed by FreakZone Games and published by ScrewAttack. As shown by The Nerd in his episode ""AVGN Games"", games about The Nerd and his angry world have existed long before this game came out. Many of those titles were homebrew titles often created by one person and released on the Internet for free. AVGN Adventures is the first commercial AVGN game and certainly the title with the highest production value. Visually, the game features rich and colorful pixel art in additional to some smoothly animated effects (The Nerd exploding into several bits and pieces a la Fallout 3 is a highlight.) The soundtrack hearkens back to the video game days of yore, featuring an engrossing score that fits right at home with the games overall difficulty as well as sound effects that further  draw you in.The gameplay is almost perfect for a game of this genre, it's hard but not unfair, and it's levels are fun and all vastly different from eachother. My only true gripe with the game is the finicky keyboard controls which unfortunately makes jumping and landing with precision challenging. This problem is of course erased when you plug in an Xbox 360 PC controller, however it does not erase the games overall difficulty. This game is not recommended for anyone who's not familiar with NES titles like Mega Man, Ninja Gaiden, and Castlevania as the difficulty of this game mimicks that of those classic titles. Also, the game doesn't have much replay value after you complete it for the first time which is acceptable for a $10 game but it would have been a nice feature to unlock additional levels or harder difficulty levels after you complete the game.It's definitely worth your money if you like hard-as-nails, old-school platformers!"
