,Recommended,237740,28353037,"Posted: 13 December, 2016",all,Kid Cuisine Cheese Blaster,"Here's what it boils down to: if you enjoy the challenge and frustration/reward ratio of classic NES titles, you will probably enjoy this game. If you don't, you absolutely, positively will not enjoy this game. And if you've never played an NES game, or at the very least never played one of the first three Mega Man games... well, ""I"" can't ""recommend"" piracy, but you should probably try playing some of that.The reason for this is that this game borrows a lot from the original Mega Man games. And Metroid and Castlevania and there's a little Ninja Gaiden in there and... well... look; basically this game is a pastiche of the best of the NES. And I've definitely seen criticism of AVGNA because it's 'using elements from games the Nerd reviewed' or something. Let me be frank. At least I can *beat* this game. Out of the 30+ NES games I own, I've completed less than a third. This game is a CAKEWALK comparatively speaking. You want impossibly difficult? Go sit down with Monster Party for a couple hours. I guarantee you'll be looking at this game differently.This isn't to say that the game is easy. A term I hear thrown around a lot among nostalgic and retro gamers is ""NES hard"". Which is to say that games from that time period, as I've said before, tended to be highly aggravating in difficulty. However, there's just no feeling of satisfaction quite like finally managing to beat an area of a classic game you've been struggling with for hours. It's honestly a bit difficult to explain what makes it different from most modern games, but I think it has to do with how cinematic current games are. Even if you struggle with a section for hours, you've primarily done it to progress a story. 'NES hard' means it's just you and the game. If there's a story, it's bare bones at best. You struggle over every obstacle just to be able to say you did. Current gaming is generally like watching a movie. Retro gaming, at least in the 80's, was more like climbing a mountain- there's nothing up there and there's no logical reason to do it, but ♥♥♥♥ it- YOU DID IT.Angry Video Game Nerd Adventures is one of the only modern games I've played that has managed to capture that feeling, albeit to a somewhat lesser degree. Like I said, the game isnt' as hard as some classic titles. And as much as I like James's work, the presence of all the reference jokes can be somewhat distracting. The soundtrack is pretty solid. I don't think it's something I'd listen to in my free time, but it works pretty well and it sounds nice.Basically, if you're waffling, refer to my first paragraph. But for me, I recommend it."
